<svg aria-label="star filled" class="AssemblyIcon AssemblyIcon--medium" role="img"><noscript></noscript><use xlink:href="#star-filled"></use><noscript></noscript></svg></span></button><div class="t1vey32f"><div tabindex="-1" class="fu3v3nt" data-testid="AssemblyTooltip--base"><button type="button" aria-label="Audio" class="bvbv8re a1qd8xfe aj47u34 ayaxb5p AssemblyIconButton AssemblyButtonBaseV2 AssemblyButtonBaseV2--medium" data-testid="assembly-icon-button-text-secondary" title="Audio" style="--button-height: 2.5rem; --content-opacity: 1;"><span class="cz3acib n17nrlic"><svg aria-label="sound" class="AssemblyIcon AssemblyIcon--medium" role="img"><noscript></noscript><use xlink:href="#audio"></use><noscript></noscript></svg></span></button></div></div></div><div class="sewpbju" style="--sewpbju-0: 0rem;"><div class="szwq4v1" style="--szwq4v1-0: 40% minmax(0, 1fr);"><div class="sfnudnq" data-testid="set-page-term-card-side"><div class="sumuxuf"><span class="s1rpwius"><span class="TermText notranslate lang-en">Each osteon includes lamellae, lacunae, canaliculi and a Haversian canal. The lamellae are concentric rings of matrix that consist of mineral salts and collagen fibers. Lacunae are small spaces between lamellae that contain mature bone cells called osteocytes. Projecting from the lacunae are canaliculi, which are networks of minute canals containing the processes of osteocytes. Canaliculi provide routes for nutrients to reach osteocytes and for wastes to leave them. A central Haversian canal contains blood vessels and nerves. Trabeculae of spongy bone have similar components but lack the haversian system. Trabeculae still contain lamellae osteocytes, lacunae, and canaliculi. The spaces within the trabeculae are filled with red bone marrow.</span></span></div></div><div class="sfnudnq" data-testid="set-page-term-card-side"><div class="sumuxuf"><div class="hm80q9a h1ql76m6"><span class="TermText notranslate lang-en">Briefly describe the four parts of an osteon and